 from whit carson u washington edu john whitmore subject re help with ultra long timing article i d shelley one pr nine one ainnikg distribution world organization university of washington seattle lines two five nntp posting host carson u washington edu in article johnh macadam mpce mq edu au john haddy writes in article mcovingt aisun three ai uga edu michael covington writes one don t use big capacitors they are unreliable for timing due to leakage true especially for electrolytic capacitors at high temperature instead use a quartz crystal and divide its frequency by two four zero times or something like that wouldn t a crystal be affected by cold my gut feeling is that as a mechanically resonating device extreme cold is likely to affect the compliance terminology of the quartz and hence its resonant frequency low power quartz oscillators are usually three two khz and these have significant temperature drifts which one doesn t often notice while wearing the watch on one s wrist low temperature sensitivity is available in other crystal types which unfortunately are larger and higher frequency one mhz or so and take more battery power programmable timers might be less accurate but they are more power stingy than suitable crystal oscillators john whitmore